text:
Today, we celebrate the journey
our graduates have taken--

focused and motivated in the
midst of a global pandemic. Inspiration is at the
heart of their story.

But so is passion, curiosity,
a thirst for knowledge,

application of the highest
intellectual standards, and asking really interesting,
important questions.

With this in mind,
let's take a moment to explore an age-old question.

Do the clothes make the person? Academic regalia dates
back to the 13th century.

Originally worn by
medieval scholars, possibly to stay warm
in unheated monasteries,

the long gowns,
hoods, and caps were adopted by English
scholars toward the end of the 14th century.

Not until the late 19th
century did Harvard faculty begin to wear academic regalia.

And today, the wearing
of academic regalia is mainly reserved
for Commencement

and other special occasions on
university and college campuses around the globe.

Of special note, the hood, worn
by holders of doctoral degrees, signifies the highest level
of academic achievement.

The traditional Doctoral
Hooding Ceremony is a part of our
diploma ceremonies

to symbolically mark the
passage from student to mastery.

Congratulations to all of our
doctoral students for reaching this important milestone.
